('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_5_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'You will not receive [icon_gold] gold, [icon_science] science, [icon_culture] culture, or [icon_faith] faith from any source.2.The anarchy has no special bonuses or state inheritance.3. Your policy does not provide any benefits and cannot be adjusted.4. You cannot change governments before the end of the anarchy government.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'With the opening of the Civic Tree, available governments will change as you move forward in time. Initially, you will have a simple government with only a few clubs. But as you arrive later, many different integrated spaces will be opened. In addition, governments have their own good; the Theocracy government, for example, will add a religious force [icon_power] to the theological war, [icon_faith] in the faith of a citizen of those cities who has administrator [icon_faith], and will allow you to buy ground cells with [icon_faith] faith and offer discounts on [icon_faith] purchases when active.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_TRADE_2_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'A player can only protect a limited number of [icon_TradeRoute] trade routes. Capacity is often determined by the number of walkways and lighting buildings maintained, but can also be increased by other means. Note that commercial highway markets and lighting buildings are not in the same city - the benefit only applies to the first you build.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_4_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'There are 6 different types of policies, and 4 political positions. All versions must be applied to vacant seats of the same type by the government, but the wild card slot can accommodate any type of policy.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_4_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_5', 'Wildcards: These policies have different strong effects, but can only be used in wildcard policy positions.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_4_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_6', 'Government: These policies provide strong inheritance benefits for different types of government. They are open when you are building the Plaza Government District and one of the buildings that corresponds to the government level. For example, if you take over the government of the normal republic, and after you build the warlord''s chair, the ancestral hall, or the audience hall, you will open the Republican heritage policy.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOVT_4_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_7', 'Black Age: If you enter the Black Age, you may be subject to certain rules that apply only while you are in the Black Age. Black Age policy selections will change as Eras progresses. These policies may give you a specific benefit that may help you, but there is a cost that may limit you in other ways.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_LEADERS_PAGE_LEADER_T_ROOSEVELT_CHAPTER_DETAILED_BODY', 'At the beginning of the game, the only American advantage is +5 [icon_force] fighting force in their home continent. They want to expand their continent quickly and move to get support in nearby cities. With their diplomatic political position turning to savages, their choice of government is important, although the Common Republic and the Trade Republic are the most profitable in the United States. They should also consider building a national history museum in place of their government. With its movie studio, National Park Bonus, and two unique post-industrial cells, it shines from the 20th century.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_COMBAT_11_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'Proclaiming war against another civilization will give you penalties for dealing with another civilization in the game, known as the Hot Penalty. This reflects a lack of confidence in other leaders or fear of your own actions. The most common way to declare war, and the most common way to calculate all wars, including punishment, is formal warfare. In this case, the civilization first indicates a target civilization and then declares an official war.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_COMBAT_11_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'The penalty is increasing, as war becomes an unacceptable solution to the conflicts between the civilizations of the world. These situations also include those you have been in. In most cases, declaring war and capturing an enemy city will give you the hottest punishment of the moment, and beating a city will give you three times the hottest punishment of the moment. Some casus belli (see casus belli section under diplomacy) may change their punishment, reduce certain actions, or make them more expensive. Other measures, such as the use of nuclear weapons, will also make a difference in your punishment.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_COMBAT_13_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'To complete a district take 3 movement points, or your entire movement. Each district building must be relied upon individually, and granted a district-based shop type. See Secretary''s main article once injected, a building can no longer be injected until it has been returned online to the owner (via a manufacturing menu and takes 25% of the value of that building''s initial construction output.)'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_SCIENCE_2_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'Science comes from a variety of sources, including your own [icon_citizen] (0.5 instead of [icon_citizen]), your own castle, some politics, some religious beliefs, some resources, miracles, business, and of course the campus district and its residents. Take a look at Civilopedia for a science source [icon_Science].'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGEGROUP_EXPANSION_NAME', 'The Promotion and Promotion'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_PRIDE_MOMENTS_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_TITLE', 'Historical Records'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_PRIDE_MOMENTS_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'Historical moments are important events that occur throughout the history of the game, from being the first to choosing a new form of government, to the establishment of a special unit, to the discovery of natural miracles. There are dozens of historical moments during the game, representing the world''s first victory with the player. The time will change according to the time.The times will change over time. For example, the cleanliness of barbarian camps in the Middle Ages is a milestone, but the cleanliness of a modern - day camp will not even qualify for recognition. You can view your date at any time while playing by clicking on the date calendar in the toolbar at the top left. [newline][newline] Any historical moment added to bridge when you come out of that moment on, which is the limit of whether you will rise to the golden age or sink into the next dark age. If you have several historical periods at once, it means that you are likely to enter the Golden Age in the following periods. If you are the first player in the world to get a certain amount of time in history, you will earn a lot of epoch points.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOLDEN_AGES_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_TITLE', 'The Golden Age and the Darkness'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOLDEN_AGES_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'As the game continues from the age of civilization you can enter the Golden Age or the Dark Age. If you are better than other civilizations or have completed many historical periods, then there is a good chance that you will enter the Golden Age in the next period. If you start falling behind, you may find yourself in the dark ages. [newline]Gold is a time of great prosperity for your people. Your loyalty will fall to a lower level than normal. Not only will your cities be more likely to remain in your civilization, but you may even become the nearest city to your civilization. Then you can choose the option for next time. Devotions are powerful tools that protect a specific part of your civilization. But know that earning the golden age is difficult to earn the next golden age, and it is easy to fall into the black age. Your loyalty decreases faster than normal, which can lead to cities on the outskirts of your civilization leaving and becoming independent cities, or beating other players and joining their civilization. You can help prevent this by using your admins [icon_governor], or strategically choosing to lose their city (which you can expect to restore later.)Don''t despair or get upset if you find yourself in a dark time because you have a chance to enter the brave era. Your limits for entering the Golden Age will decrease if you are in the Dark Age, and if you cross the limits of the Golden Age, you will enter the Brave Age. The hero''s parents will allow you to choose from three devotions for next season! This can really put you ahead of the player in the Golden Age of the Golden Age, if you could make the most of your talent.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOLDEN_AGES_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'If you are above the black age, but do not have enough high scores to enter the Golden Age, you enter the usual age. During the normal age you can still opt for dedication at this age, but you will not receive any other bonuses or penalties.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOLDEN_AGES_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_3', 'Dark times also give you access to special dark times policies. Wild card policies can give you options to get out of the dark ages, but they can be expensive. For example, the isolation policy provides bonuses for domestic business routes [icon_TradeRoute], but it prevents you from building or buying settlements or setting up new cities.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_GOLDEN_AGES_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_4', 'You may have to complete deductions during the ordinary and dark ages to increase your period scores, which gives you the perfect opportunity to earn a future golden age.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_LOYALTY_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_TITLE', 'The sincerity'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_LOYALTY_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_1', 'Honesty is the measure of a city devoted to its civilization. Each city has a loyalty value of 0 to 100, which reflects how many citizens [icon_citizen] in the city want to remain as part of your civilization. When loyalty decreases to 75, city productivity and growth are penalized by 25%. When loyalty decreases to 25, city productivity is penalized by 50% growth and punished by 75%. When loyalty reaches 0, the city rises up against the landlord and becomes a free city. Free cities are uncivilized and are trying to defend themselves against military intervention. If the loyalty of the Free City falls to 0, its independence attempt fails, and they are seeking to enter civilization. Which civilization is asked to join depends on who imposes most of the pressure on the free city during their independence. In this way, a free city can safely bring into your civilization (or well into your civilization).'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_LOYALTY_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_2', 'Integrity changes each cycle based on many factors, but the most important is the pressure of the citizen [icon_citizen] living in or near the city. If [icon_city] pressures are higher than those of other civilizations, the integrity of the city will increase (up to +20 per second). If the other pressures of civilization are strong, the integrity of the city will decrease (up to -20 per turn). Each citizen (icon_citizen) performs a baseline pressure of 1, but it can be reversed. For example, [icon_city] citizens living in a capital are still under pressure 1. The golden and brave age adds 0.5 to all citizens [icon_citizen], while the black age brings it down to 0.5. This pressure [icon_citizen] has an impact on cities in 9 drawers, but it is 10% less effective than a remote part.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_LOYALTY_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_3', 'The percentage of [icon_governor] in city and happiness is another strong factor that affects the integrity of the city per cycle. In addition, cities that have been beaten by military forces will receive loyalty penalties based on having complaints from the original owner of the city, but these can be lowered by maintaining a military unit that has taken over the city. Use loyalty glasses to identify loyalty issues, including sources of pressure in nearby cities. A full description of the factors affecting the integrity of the city can be found in the Integrity and City Board Governor section.'),
('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CONCEPTS_PAGE_LOYALTY_1_CHAPTER_CONTENT_PARA_4', 'For players who have established a religion, cities get +3 honesty to follow that religion, but -3 honesty to each turn if they follow the religion of another player.'),
