('en_US', 'LOC_PEDIA_CIVILIZATIONS_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_BYZANTIUM_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', 'The Byzantine Empire refers to the eastern part of the Roman Empire. Its inhabitants did not know the name "Byzantine," but it was used by historians. It refers to the name of the village where Constantine was going to find Constantinople (now Istanbul; Constantinople has found the job). The Eastern/Western division is based on a fundamental culture, language, and political division across the Mediterranean, with one that reflects subsequent divisions between Orthodox (Eastern) and Catholic (Western). Byzantium continued the legacy of Roman development and presence in the region until the Ottomans conquered it in 1453 and made a great impact in Eastern Europe.'),
